b'' b': the single launch core station concept. a shuttle external tank and solid' b': rocket boosters would be used to launch the station into orbit. shuttle' b': main engines would be mounted to the tail of the station module for launch' b': and jettisoned after et separation.' b'' b': why jettison the ssmes? why not hold on to them and have a shuttle' b': bring them down to use as spares?' b'' b"one performance reason comes to mind: if you jettison the ssme's, you" b"don't have to drag them with you when you perform your circularization" b"burn(s). on-orbit, ssme's are just dead weight, since we don't have an" b'ssme h2/o2 pressurization mechanism which works in zero-g. this means' b"that you can't use them for re-boost or anything else. dead weight has" b'a couple of advantages, but more disadvantages.' b'' b"throw-away ssme's might let us use some of the old ssme's which are not-" b"quite-man-ratable. but i doubt we'd do that; the cost of a launch" b'failure is too high.' b'' b'-- ken jenks, nasa/jsc/gm2, space shuttle program office' b'' b'"...development of the space station is as inevitable as' b'the rising of the sun." wernher von braun' 